photo.description: An interesting collection of early German MSS. and printed books. The 'Vorbericht' explains that Fallersleben having been deprived of his Professorship at Breslau for publishing his 'Unpolitischen Lieder' in 1841 was forced to part with his library which he had gathered with such love and enthusiasm over a period of 30 years. Some of his books had already found their way to the auction room in May 1843. The remainder, here cataloged, which comprised the larger and more valuable portion of his library having failed to find a buyer among the 'public' libraries of his own country he now offered to 'all the world' for 2000 Thalers. photo.description: Autograph of Wilhelm Michel (1877-1942), German writer and the author of this work. (Penn's copy is number 18 of a limited edition of 400, of which 30 were printed on hand-made paper, bound in leather and signed by the author.) Michel received the Georg-Büchner-Preis in 1925. From 1906 to 1930 he contributed regularly to the leftist magazine Die Weltbühne, edited by Nobel Peace Prize winner Carl von Ossietzky, with whom Michel clashed in 1933 over the staging of Bertolt Brecht's Saint Joan of the Stockyards (which Michel characterized as "an artistically disguised attempt to kill our soul"). photo.description: Binding: decorative paper boards with initials ("SWF") of Samuel W. Fernberger in gold ink(?) on left board. [Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956) received his Ph.D. in psychology from the University of Pennsylvania in 1912 and was a member of the faculty at Clark University from 1912 until his death. F. W. Irwin wrote in Fernberger's obituary in The American Journal of Psychology, Vol. 69.4 (1956), p. 677-678: "At all stages of his career he exhibited an interest in those applications of experimental psychology that employed rigorous, preferably psychophysical, methods. He once testified before the Public Service Commission of Pennsylvania as an expert for the complainant in an action brought by the Yellow Cab Company of Philadelphia to prevent the use by others of taxicabs with colors alleged to resemble too closely the color of Yellow Cabs. His testimony involved not only verbal opinions but also the performance of demonstrations in the hearing room in the presence of the examiner and the interested parties. He mixed colors on a rotary color mixer to match the colors of the complainant's and respondent's cabs, showed that they were closely similar -- they differed by not more than three just noticeable differences along the base of a model of the color solid that was also produced -- and that their resemblance increased as the illumination of the room was decreased." Shortly before his death Fernberger donated a collection of psychological books and journals to the University of Pennsylvania as the Samuel W. Fernberger Collection of Psychology. Established heading: Fernberger, Samuel Weiller, 1887-1956]. Other examples of Samuel Weiller Fernberger provenance Penn Libraries call number: GC8 H4136 824p All images from this book

photo.description: Bookplate of Dr. Bradley H. Kirschberg (1883?-1941), chemist and head of the New York State Police Laboratory. Born in Poland, he immigrated to the United States and took a doctorate in chemistry from New York University. From 1912-1935 he served as city chemist for Schenectady. In 1936 he was appointed director of the New York State Police Laboratory, in which position he served until his death. (According to his obituary in the New York Times (29 May 1941), he died of a heart attack on the job.) Not established. Penn Libraries call number: RC9 T7564 932h 1936

photo.description: Eugene Morris Pharo (1893-1945) son of Allen Ridgway Pharo and Anna Leeds Ogborn Pharo was a newspaper journalist, writer and captain in the U.S. Army. He attended Westtown Prep School in Westchester Pa. and was a graduate of Haverford College (1915) where he wrote for the Haverfordian. In 1917 he married Mary Reed Macpherson, with whom he had 4 daughters and a son, residing for a time in Moorestown, NJ. After graduating from Haverford he wrote for a Philadelphia paper (unidentified) and was later a reporter for the Atlantic City Review. During the 1920s he wrote for American serial publications “Everybody’s magazine” “The Smart Set” and “American Mercury” (founded by H.L. Mencken). Pharo eventually became the city editor of the Washington Post. He died Mar. 2, 1945 in Valley Forge Military Hospital after contracting an illness during his years serving in the AMG (Allied Military Government) in London. Cf. The biographical catalog of the matriculates of Haverford College, together with lists of the members of the college faculty and the managers, officers and recipients of honorary degrees, 1833-1922. www26.us.archive.org/stream/haverfordianvols3637have#page... www26.us.archive.org/stream/haverfordianvols3839have#page... NYT Obituary: query.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=F50B16F9345C1B7B93C... search.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?gss=angs-g&gsfn=e... Search for “Eugene Pharo” in Burlington County Library System Newspaper Notices Index. www.bcls.lib.nj.us/newspapers/nni/ Penn Libraries call number: PolC9 P9589 Eg920t

photo.description: According to a ms. note in this volume, this is the ownership inscription of Heinsius ("Ton 'Einsius"). Heinsius could be either Daniel Heinsius (1580-1655), classical scholar and librarian of Leiden University Library or his son Nicolaas Heinsius (1620-1681) a Dutch philologist and poet and book collector whose large library was auctioned after his death with a catalog "Bibliotheca Heinsiana, sive, Catalogus librorum, quos magno studio & sumtu, dum viveret, collegit" (1682). The same edition of this work (Gnōmologiai palaiotatōn poiētōn) is listed on p. 75 of the " Bibliotheca Heinsiana" (Cf. books.google.com/books?id=P2Y7AAAAcAAJ&printsec=front... ) To complicate matters Harvard records that their copy of this title held at Houghton Library (OCLC #613850347) was owned by Nicolaas Heinsius and bears his ownership mark: Ex Biblioth. Heinsii Lugduni Batauor. CD D C LXXXIII. Other than the "Ton "Einsius" title page marking there are no other marks of ownership suggesting a Heinsius provenance nor does this copy have annotations. For these reasons it is not clear that this copy was actually owned by Heinsius unless there were 2 copies sold. Perhaps the marking refers to a different Heinsius altogether or is simply a note stating that he (Nicolaas) owned a copy of this work. Established heading: Heinsius, Daniel, 1580-1655 Established heading: Hensius, Nicolaas, 1620-1681 Penn Libraries call number: GrC A100 553g All images from this book

photo.description: Stamp of the Wissenschaftliches Institut der Elsass-Lothringer im Reich, Frankfurt am Main, Germany. According to this page of the library website of the Goethe Universität Frankfurt am Main, "The Wissenschaftliches Institut der Elsass-Lothringer im Reich was founded at the Universität Frankfurt am Main in 1921 with the goal of serving 'the common economic and cultural interests of Alsace-Lorraine in the kingdom to the exclusion of political efforts.' In the year 1963 the Erwin von Steinbach-Stiftung and the University library concluded a deposit agreement for the collection of the Wissenschaftliches Institut der Elsass-Lothringer im Reich by which the Institut's library with its more than 25000 volumes and the remainder of its archives were given on permanent loan to the Stadt- und Universitätsbibliothek Frankfurt am Main." photo.description: Bookseller's reproduction of the bookplate of Maria Benigna Francisca Piccolomini (1635-1701) which appears in this volume. The exlibris has long been misidentified as ''Markgraf Ludwig von Baden''. Cf. E. Raffel, In Europa Gedruckt, in Weimar Gesammelt in H. Seemann's Europa in Weimar: Visionen eines Kontinents, p. 76. Maria Benigna Francisca of Saxony, Angria and Westphalia, was the daughter of Julius Henry of Saxe-Lauenburg (1586-1665) and wife of Ottavio Piccolomini-Pieri, duca d’Amalfi (1599-1656). This book comes from the Troilo Piccolomini Library, formed originally by her father. Cf. her entry in Wikipedia. Piccolomini's library was given to the Piarist college in Schlackenwerth (now Ostrov, Czech Republic), founded in 1666 and disbanded in 1876. Cf. W. Sommer, Kurze Geschichte der Stadt Schlackenwerth in Verbindung mit dem Piaristen-Collegium (Schlackenwerth, 1866). According to this entry in the Yale Law Library Rare Books Blog, "[m]ajor donations to the library included the collection of Princess Maria Piccolomini." Her father, Julius Henry of Saxe-Lauenburg (1586-1665) had property interests in Ostrov, and her husband, Ottavio Piccolomini-Pieri, duca d’Amalfi (1599-1656) campaigned there. Other images of books from Maria Benigna Francisca Piccolomini's library. Established heading: Piccolomini, Maria Benigna Francisca 1635-1701 Established heading: Ludwig Wilhelm I, Margrave of Baden, 1655-1707 Penn Libraries call number: GC5 W6453 546t All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record (work 1) Penn Libraries catalog record (work 2)

photo.description: Bookplate of Kloster Kreuzberg, an observant Franciscan house near Bischofsheim, Bavaria, Germany, founded in 1685. Though the monastery was formally secularized in 1803, a small number of monks persisted at the site and in 1826 King Ludwig I of Bavaria issued a decree permitting them to accept novices again. Today the monastery is notable both as a pilgrimage site (to the crucifixes whence its name derives) and for its brewery. Penn Libraries call number: GC5 W6440 544o 1587 All images from this book

photo.description:
M[a]g[iste]r Christophorus goltgrucker[?] emit hu[n]c libru[m] A Venerando
uiro Ioanne Palch 50 [...] Anno .M.D.decimosexto.

-- Rotat omne fatum --

Conrad[us] hoffman emit hunc libru[m] A venerando viro M. Crist:
goltgruber[?] 40 [...] Anno. M.D.decimooctauo

Constat 40.4[?]

[An early 16th-century ms. inscription regarding the purchase of this book by Christophorus Goltgruber [or Goltgrucker] from Joannes Palch in 1516, followed by a Latin maxim, followed by another 16th-century ms. inscription regarding the purchase of this book by Conradus Hoffman from Christophorus Goltgruber [or Goltgrucker] in 1518. The difficulty is that Hoffmann appears to record Christophorus's surname as "Goltgruber" (== Goldgruber), but Christophorus himself seems to have written "Goltgrucker".

Penn Libraries call number: GC5 T7776 501s
photo.title: Inscriptions recording the purchase of this book by Chrisophorus Goltgruber [Goltgrucker?] in 1516 and by Conradus Hoffman in 1518
